=============== 11.  Research Challenges and Difficulties
"Every research project faces challenges, and our study on epileptic seizure prediction is no exception. Here, I will highlight three key difficulties that impacted our research and discuss their implications."

ğŸ“Œ 1. Limited Data Availability
Obtaining high-quality EEG data is difficult, as there are very few publicly available datasets.
Our final dataset contained only around 10,000 samples, sourced from a single public database.
Generalization remains a concernâ€”since our data is limited, the model's performance on unseen clinical data may not be optimal.
Even though we collaborated with hospitals, access to clinical EEG data was very restricted, making it hard to improve model robustness.
This limitation is evident in our clinical trial results, which show a drop in performance when tested on real-world patient data.
ğŸ“Œ 2. Computational Constraints at the Time
Five years ago, computing power was far more limited compared to today.
Deep learning models require substantial computational resources, but at that time, high-performance GPUs were not as common or accessible.
This constraint restricted the size of our training dataset and the complexity of our model architectures.
With todayâ€™s advancements in hardware, we believe that training on larger EEG datasets would significantly improve model accuracy and generalization.
ğŸ“Œ 3. Pre-feature Selection and Model Input Optimization
While CNNs can learn features automatically, our initial approach of using raw EEG signals as input did not yield good results.
EEG signals have complex frequency-domain characteristics, which are not well captured by direct time-domain analysis.
To address this, we explored frequency-domain features:
Converted EEG signals into frequency representations.
Applied basic processing techniques to enhance signal clarity before feeding it into the CNN.
This significantly improved model performance, showing that pre-processing EEG data before deep learning is crucial.
ğŸ“Œ Summary
*"In summary, the three biggest challenges were:

Limited dataset size, leading to generalization issues.
Computational constraints at the time, restricting model training.
Feature selectionâ€”shifting from raw EEG signals to frequency-domain transformations improved performance.
As computing power increases and more clinical EEG data becomes available, we believe that future models will achieve much higher accuracy and reliability."*


